        <div class="jumbotron text-center" id="particles-js">
            <h1>AdHocEd</h1>
            <p>Welcome to AdHocEd, an educational application for students and teachers
                 with graphical representation of Mobile Computing algorithms for Ad Hoc networks.
                Create a free account to be able to save the graphs you design in the editor.</p>
            <div class="btn btn-default btn-block home-btn text-center" id="btn_logIn">Log In</div>
            <div class="btn btn-default btn-block home-btn text-center" id="btn_SignUp">Sign Up</div>
        </div>
        <div id="main_panel">
            <section>
                <article>
                    <h4>Overview</h4>
                    <p>Visually aid the professor's teaching and students' studying of 
                        the Ad Hoc networking algorithms assosiated with "Mobile 
                        and Ad Hoc Computing". Design an Ad Hoc network graph with the editor tools and choose 
                        from a list of algorithms to run. The results and the steps 
                        of the execution will be presented both in the graph and as text. 
                        Made as a practise tool for students who take Ad Hoc networking classes and as a presentation
                         tool for teachers, replacing the blackboard.</p>
                </article>
                <article>
                    <h4>Editor Features</h4>
                    <p>Use the editor tools to construct a network graph. 
                        You can add, remove and link nodes, as well as save and load your graphs, 
                        instead of drawing them from the beginning every time. Use the instructions button on the top left 
                        to get information about the tools. 
                    </p>
                    <img src='imgs/home_page_img1.png'></img>
                    <img src='imgs/home_page_img2.png' class="right_floater"></img>
                </article>
                <article>
                    <h4>Algorithm Analysis</h4>
                    <p>Select one of the supported algorithms and press the execute button to see the results.
                        The "Algorithm Analysis" panel will show you the steps of the 
                        execution in clickable "step boxes". When you click a "step box" you can 
                        see the result of the current execution step in the graph.
                    </p>
                    <img src='imgs/home_page_img3.png'></img>
                    <img src='imgs/home_page_img4.png' class="right_floater"></img>
                </article>
                <article>
                    <h4>Supported Algorithms</h4>
